    "title": "Slow-roast beef brisket",
    "subtitle": "Four hours low and slow until sliceable and yielding",
    "excerpt": "Beef brisket braised in stock and red wine at a low temperature for four hours until it slices cleanly but falls apart at the edges. A cheaper cut that rewards patience.",
    "sourceNotes": "Mrs Beeton, Book of Household Management (1861), Project Gutenberg #10136. Boiled and braised beef methods.\n\nEliza Acton, Modern Cookery for Private Families (1845). Pot-roasted and braised beef.",
    "body": {
      "type": "doc",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Brisket is a working muscle with a high collagen content that makes it tough when cooked quickly and yielding when cooked slowly. Four hours at 150 degrees C in a covered casserole with stock and red wine converts the collagen to gelatin, producing meat that slices cleanly and collapses at the edges. It is the best value roasting beef available.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
