        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Method",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Sear and build the braise",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Heat the oven to 150 degrees C fan. Pat the brisket dry and season generously with salt. Heat the oil in a casserole over high heat and sear the brisket on all sides until deeply browned, about 3 to 4 minutes per side. Remove and set aside.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Reduce the heat to medium. Add the onion, carrot, and celery to the casserole and cook for 5 minutes until starting to soften. Add the garlic and cook for 1 minute more.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Pour in the red wine and let it bubble for 2 minutes. Add the hot stock, thyme, and bay leaves. Return the brisket on top of the vegetables, fat-side up.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Braise and rest",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Cover tightly and ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "braise",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmp5pp2dg0000jcv4mbsuedx3"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " in the oven for 4 hours. Check at 2 hours and add a splash of stock or water if the liquid level has dropped significantly.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "The brisket is ready when it ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "slow-roasted",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmpsohsur000034v48hvh5qjr"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " to full tenderness: a skewer should pass through with no resistance. Transfer to a board and rest for 20 minutes. Strain the cooking juices and serve alongside.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "troubleshooter",
          "attrs": {
            "items": [
              {
                "fix": "Continue cooking: brisket can take up to 5 hours. Ensure the lid seals properly. If it does not, place a sheet of greaseproof paper under the lid.",
                "cause": "A cold joint went in without searing, or the casserole lid was not tight.",
                "symptom": "The brisket is still very tough after 4 hours"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Check at 2 hours and add more hot stock if needed. The liquid level should sit about halfway up the meat.",
                "cause": "Not enough liquid was added, or the casserole was not tightly covered.",
                "symptom": "The cooking liquid has reduced to a sticky mass and is threatening to burn"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Pull the brisket apart with two forks and serve as pulled beef. This is not a failure: pulled brisket is excellent.",
                "cause": "Overcooked beyond the sliceable stage.",
                "symptom": "The meat falls apart completely and cannot be sliced"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Always sear before braising. Reduce the strained juices on the hob over medium heat for 10 minutes to concentrate.",
                "cause": "The searing step was skipped, removing the fond (browned residue) that builds flavour.",
                "symptom": "The cooking juices are thin and lack flavour"
              }
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Variations",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Add a tablespoon of tomato puree with the wine for a richer, darker sauce. A few anchovy fillets dissolved into the vegetables before the wine adds depth without a fishy flavour. For a simpler weekday version, skip the searing and add everything cold to the casserole: the flavour is less complex but the method is entirely hands-off.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Where this dish lives",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Pot-roasted brisket is a working-class British and Jewish cooking tradition. The brisket was the affordable cut that tough-cooked into a tender Sunday meal. Food writer Eliza Acton and Victorian cookery writer Mrs Beeton both described similar slow-braised beef methods. Brisket fell out of favour when cheaper cuts became available. It has returned through barbecue culture and renewed interest in economical cooking.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
